
[1]auricle

   AU'RICLE, n. [L. auricula, dim. from auris, the ear.]

   1. The external ear, or that part which is prominent from the heat.

   2. The auricles of the heart are two muscular bags, situated at the
   base, serving as diverticula for the blood, during the diastole. They
   resemble the auricle of the ear, and cover the ventricles of the heart,
   like caps. Their systole of the heart, and vice versa. They receive the
   blood from the veins, and communicate it to the ventricles.
